content:
{
  "schemaVersion": 3,
  "judgeId": "judge_1",
  "batchIndex": 1,
  "comparisons": [
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "c4_rock_pool_tides",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2's mechanism of crafting bamboo traps from scraps perfectly embodies 'reinvesting in tools' and scales logically. Its Ch 21-30 conflict (releasing egg-bearing crabs) directly addresses the 'sustainable livelihood' boundary, whereas c4 relies heavily on extreme physical gathering which is harder to scale."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "c5_shrimp_paste",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 focuses on active fishing, fitting 'proactively turning sea knowledge into catches'. c2's Ch 21-30 limit is an active choice about resource sustainability (spawning season), whereas c5 relies on an external disease outbreak, missing the core intent of the sustainability boundary."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "c6_handline_bait",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 scales logically through crafting more traps, fitting the 1980s setting and 'getting rich through skills'. c6 relies on a secret bait formula to catch huge fish, which leans slightly towards a 'golden finger' advantage compared to c2's grounded progression."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "c7_live_seafood_transport",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 is a pure fishing concept that perfectly hits all commission requirements. c7 focuses on logistics and mechanical aeration, which is creative but shifts the focus away from 'sea knowledge into catches' towards transport."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "c8_light_luring_squid",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2's use of scrap bamboo to make traps is a perfect 'zero-cost' grounded start for the 1980s. c2's Ch 21-30 conflict (egg-bearing crabs) is a stronger, more emotional sustainability choice than c8's light pollution issue."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "c9_oyster_spat_poles",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c9 (oyster poles) requires months to yield, violating the 'short difficulties, early results' and 'Ch 1-3 must have money/meals' requirements. c2 provides immediate, satisfying results within the first 3 chapters."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "c10_net_modifications",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 involves the MC directly going to sea and catching seafood, fulfilling the core fantasy. c10 has the MC acting as a mechanic/net repairman for others, which makes him dependent on other boat owners and dilutes the 'proactive catch' experience."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_01",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2's Ch 21-30 conflict (spawning crabs) perfectly matches the boundary requiring a choice between fast profit and sustainable livelihood. dt_01_concept_01's conflict is market competition, which fails the specific biological resource limit boundary."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_02",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 uses traditional, grounded sea knowledge. dt_01_concept_02 uses modern biotech/microbiology knowledge, which violates the boundary 'No modern tech beyond late 1980s conditions' in spirit, making the MC feel too modern."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_03",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 fulfills the 'going to sea' and 'catches' requirements directly. dt_01_concept_03 is a shore-based mechanic concept, which misses the core fishing fantasy requested by the commission."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_04",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2's trap crafting and tide reading offer a more engaging and dynamic mechanism than dt_01_concept_04's seaweed gathering. c2's progression from 3 to 15 traps to a team is highly serializable."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_05",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 is a direct fishing concept. dt_01_concept_05 focuses on ice storage and logistics, which, while important, doesn't deliver the primary 'sea knowledge into catches' experience as strongly as c2."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_06",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 focuses on catching seafood, directly answering the prompt. dt_01_concept_06 focuses on boat modification, which is a support skill and doesn't provide the same satisfying loop of catching and selling."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_07",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2's Ch 21-30 conflict is a direct choice about resource sustainability (spawning crabs). dt_01_concept_07's conflict is a natural scarcity (current change), which doesn't force the MC to make a moral/sustainable choice against fast profit."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_08",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 relies on general knowledge of tides and crab behavior, fitting the rules. dt_01_concept_08 relies on future knowledge of where the cockles moved, which violates the boundary 'No future memory as exact coordinates'."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_09",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 is a fishing concept with a clear biological resource limit. dt_01_concept_09 is about salt sorting, which lacks a true biological resource limit in Ch 21-30 (it uses weather/rain instead), missing the sustainability boundary."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "rightId": "dt_01_concept_10",
      "winnerId": "c2_bamboo_traps",
      "reason": "c2 is perfectly grounded in the 1980s poverty setting. dt_01_concept_10 focuses on eco-tourism, which is highly anachronistic for a poor Vietnamese fishing village in 1988 and violates the grounded tone."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c3_sun_drying_fish",
      "rightId": "c4_rock_pool_tides",
      "winnerId": "c3_sun_drying_fish",
      "reason": "c3's mechanism of sun-drying fish is highly detailed and scales naturally (more mats, hiring labor). Its Ch 21-30 conflict (refusing chemicals for natural preservation) perfectly fits the sustainability/integrity boundary. c4 relies on extreme physical gathering, which is harder to scale sustainably."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c3_sun_drying_fish",
      "rightId": "c5_shrimp_paste",
      "winnerId": "c3_sun_drying_fish",
      "reason": "c3's Ch 21-30 conflict (chemical vs natural) is an active choice about product integrity and sustainability. c5's conflict is an external disease outbreak, which doesn't force the MC to choose between fast profit and sustainable livelihood in the way the prompt requires."
    },
    {
      "leftId": "c3_sun_drying_fish",
      "rightId": "c6_handline_bait",
      "winnerId": "c3_sun_drying_fish",
      "reason": "c3's progression from buying cheap fish to building a drying yard is a very solid, grounded 1980s business loop. c6 relies on a secret bait formula to catch huge fish, which feels slightly more reliant on a 'golden finger' compared to c3's hard work and weather-dependent mechanism."
    }
  ]
}
